Meanwhile, the Maine ICE Watch hotline, which residents can [call to report potential sightings](https://www.pressherald.com/2025/10/27/maine-immigrant-advocacy-groups-launch-ice-activity-hotline-as-they-struggle-to-get-answers-on-arrests/) of immigration agents, has seen a surge in calls over the past week, according to one volunteer for the hotline who asked not to be named out of concern for their safety.

“There’s a lot of panic and fear among the immigrant communities,” the volunteer said. “It’s a really busy time. Everyone’s on heightened alert.”

When the hotline receives a claim that immigration officials have been spotted, the operator asks questions to ensure the call is legitimate before reaching out to verifiers, who head to the location where agents have been reported to confirm the activity.

