One Maine mother who was detained by ICE and transported to Louisiana tried to no avail to communicate to agents that she is a U.S.-born citizen and had papers to prove it, Saciid-Siice said. After family members presented identification ranging from passport to birth certificate, ICE officials still did not release her.

The only thing the mother was guilty of was having a foreign-sounding last name, Saciid-Siice said.

“It’s scary, and some people are afraid to send their children to school, to go to work,” she said. “Some businesses are afraid to open their doors, and some people who bought homes are thinking of selling because of the instability.”

Some parents in Portland have [avoided walking their kids to school](https://www.pressherald.com/2026/01/13/rumors-of-ice-presence-increase-anxiety-at-portland-schools/) in recent days, while others have kept their children home entirely. In September, Portland school officials said the [community was rattled](https://www.pressherald.com/2025/09/12/detention-of-parent-near-portland-school-is-traumatic-for-community-board-chair-says/) after ICE agents who initially refused to identify themselves detained a parent during student drop-off near Gerald E. Talbot Community School.

